 generationally popular Broadway show. But big-deal musicals with catchy so=
ngs (<i>The Greatest Showman</i>), major stars (<i>La La Land</i>), and mar=
quee characters (<i>Les Mis=C3=A9rables</i>) tend to leg out, regardless. A=
dd to this the fact that, amid the theatrical industry=E2=80=99s slow-roll =
recovery, post-debut multiples have actually increased compared to the prev=
ious decade. <br/><br/>This pattern applies to films both big (<i>Twisters =
</i>earning $268 million from an $81 million debut) and small (<i>Longlegs<=
/i>, with $74 million from a $22 million launch). Sometimes, audiences are =
checking out <i>Deadpool &amp; Wolverine </i>(which had a better weekend-to=
-final gross multiple than <i>Deadpool, Deadpool 2</i>, and <i>Logan</i>) i=
n the second week, or sampling <i>The
Fall Guy </i>(which earned $93 million from that underwhelming $28 million =
debut) in theaters long after it debuted on P.V.O.D. The return of the long=
 tail is among the past year=E2=80=99s most promising theatrical trends. <b=
r/></td>
